ht on identity exclusion and subjectivity that fuels identity strategizing and agency, and recommend reforms, including naming Black Canadians an independent designated group, and combining multiculturalism and official bilingualism to strengthen belongingness among Blacks and other marginalized communities and to build the inclusive future that we long for.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aBlack peoplezAlbertaxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aCritical race theoryzCanada. 0aFrench-CanadianszAlbertaxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aImmigrantszAlbertaxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aLanguage policyzAlberta. 0aLinguistic minoritieszAlbertaxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aRacismzCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aCooper, Afua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311127221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021z978311127464540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9782763755786?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9782763755786423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9782763755786/original  a978-3-11-127221-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-127464-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles